Takeda AACT Analysis

Meera Y. Patel, M.D.

2021-01-17

library(tidyverse)
library(pg13)
library(ggplot2)

Clinical Trials associated with Takeda are queried by looping a search for the phrase “Takeda” over each field in the CTGOV.STUDIES Table in the AACT Database.

conn <- local_connect("aact")

studies_fields <-
ls_fields(conn = conn,
          schema = "ctgov",
          table = "studies")

takeda_studies <- list()
for (i in seq_along(studies_fields)) {
  studies_field <- studies_fields[i]
  sql_statement <-
  SqlRender::render(
    "SELECT *
    FROM ctgov.studies s
    WHERE LOWER(s.@studies_field::varchar) LIKE LOWER('%Takeda%')",
    studies_field = studies_field
  )
  takeda_studies[[i]] <-
    query(conn = conn,
          sql_statement = sql_statement)
}

dc(conn = conn)

takeda_studies2 <-
  takeda_studies %>%
  bind_rows() %>%
  distinct()

The overall status describes that stage at which a given ClinicalTrial is at and gives an idea of the ClinicalTrial activity as a whole at Takeda.

ggplot(data =
         takeda_studies2 %>%
           count(overall_status) %>%
           rename(`Overall Status` = overall_status,
                  Count = n),
      mapping = aes(x = `Overall Status`,
                    y = Count,
                    fill = `Overall Status`,
                    label = Count)) +
  geom_col() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Takeda Studies Across all Phases") +
  geom_text(aes(label=Count), vjust=-0.2, color="black", size=3.5)+
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Paired") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30))

“Active Statuses” are statuses that are potential targets for ongoing data cleaning efforts before the study is closed and the database is locked. Here, it is arbitrarily defined as those with overall status of “Active, not recruiting”, “Available”, and “Recruiting”.

For all studies that are currently active according to the definition above, the total actual or anticipated enrollment is calculated. This calculation gives an idea of the total number of patients that are covered by a data visualization tool like Platypus.

active_statuses <- c("Active, not recruiting",
                     "Available",
                     "Recruiting")

takeda_studies3 <-
  takeda_studies2 %>%
  filter(overall_status %in% active_statuses)

ggplot(data =
         takeda_studies3 %>%
         mutate_at(vars(enrollment_type), ~ifelse(is.na(.), "NA", .)) %>%
         group_by(enrollment_type) %>%
         summarize(total = sum(enrollment)) %>%
         rename(`Enrollment Type` = enrollment_type,
                `Total` = total),
       mapping = aes(x = `Enrollment Type`,
                     y = Total,
                     fill = `Enrollment Type`,
                     label = Total)) +
  geom_col() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Takeda Active Studies Enrollment") +
  geom_text(aes(label=Total), vjust=-0.2, color="black", size=3.5)+
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Paired") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30))

Since each study can be in various phases, which would require different degree of medical review, the active studies are further broken down by phase. Non-interventional studies are summarized by subtypes “Observational” and “Expanded Access”.

takeda_studies4 <-
  takeda_studies3 %>%
  mutate(phase = coalesce(phase, study_type)) %>%
  mutate(phase = factor(phase,
                        levels = c("Phase 1",
                                   "Phase 1/Phase 2",
                                   "Phase 2",
                                   "Phase 2/Phase 3",
                                   "Phase 3",
                                   "Phase 4",
                                   "Observational",
                                   "Observational [Patient Registry]",
                                   "Expanded Access"))) %>%
  mutate(study_type = factor(study_type,
                             levels =
                               c("Interventional",
                                 "Observational",
                                 "Observational [Patient Registry]",
                                 "Expanded Access")))

ggplot(data =
         takeda_studies4 %>%
         group_by(phase) %>%
         mutate(n = length(phase)) %>%
         ungroup() %>%
         rename(Phase = phase,
                Count = n,
                `Study Type` = study_type),
       mapping = aes(x = Phase,
                     y = Count,
                     fill = `Study Type`)) +
  geom_col() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Takeda Active Studies by Study Type and Phase") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Paired") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30))

Since each new study could mean a new Platypus project, the total number of new studies by yearm grouped by phase, are calculated.

ggplot(data =
         takeda_studies4 %>%
         rubix::filter_at_grepl(col = phase,
                                grepl_phrase = "Phase",
                                ignore.case = FALSE) %>%
         mutate(start_year = lubridate::year(start_date)) %>%
         group_by(phase,start_year) %>%
         mutate(n = length(phase)) %>%
         ungroup() %>%
         rename(Phase = phase,
                `Start Year` = start_year,
                Count = n),
       mapping = aes(x = `Start Year`,
                     y = Count,
                     fill = Phase)) +
  geom_col() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Takeda New Active Investigational Studies by Year") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Paired") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30),
        legend.position = "bottom")

Conversely, each completed study could mean either a bump in workload (activities to close a database) and/or a removal of a project from the Platypus portfolio. The number of completed studies by year, grouped by phase, is calculated.

ggplot(data =
         takeda_studies2 %>%
         rubix::filter_at_grepl(col = phase,
                                grepl_phrase = "Phase",
                                ignore.case = FALSE) %>%
         filter(overall_status %in% c("Completed")) %>%
         mutate(completion_year = lubridate::year(completion_date)) %>%
         group_by(phase,completion_year) %>%
         mutate(n = length(phase)) %>%
         ungroup() %>%
         rename(Phase = phase,
                `Completion Year` = completion_year,
                Count = n),
       mapping = aes(x = `Completion Year`,
                     y = Count,
                     fill = Phase)) +
  geom_col() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Takeda Completed Investigational Studies by Year") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Paired") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30),
        legend.position = "bottom")

I also want to see the distribution of study length from start to completion by phase. This would translate into the length of time a given study would be in the Platypus portfolio as it is being monitored for medical review.

ggplot(data =
         takeda_studies2 %>%
         rubix::filter_at_grepl(col = phase,
                                grepl_phrase = "Phase",
                                ignore.case = FALSE) %>%
         filter(overall_status %in% c("Completed")) %>%
         mutate(years_to_complete = (as.numeric(difftime(completion_date,
                                             start_date,
                                             units = "weeks")))/52) %>%
         rename(Phase = phase),
       mapping = aes(x = Phase,
                     y = years_to_complete,
                     group = Phase,
                     fill = Phase)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Takeda Completed Investigational Studies by Year",
       y = "Years to Completion") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Paired") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30),
        legend.position = "right")

Since the study time length is a common topic of discussion in drug discovery, the analysis above is repeated with all completed studies in the AACT database that started on or after 01-01-1990.

conn <- local_connect("aact")
all_data <-
  query(conn = conn,
        sql_statement =
          "SELECT DISTINCT nct_id, phase, start_date, completion_date
        FROM ctgov.studies
        WHERE overall_status = 'Completed'
        AND study_type = 'Interventional'")
dc(conn = conn)

ggplot(data =
         all_data %>%
         rubix::filter_at_grepl(col = phase,
                                grepl_phrase = "Phase",
                                ignore.case = FALSE) %>%
         filter(start_date >= as.Date("1990-01-01")) %>%
         filter(completion_date > start_date) %>%
         mutate(years_to_complete = (as.numeric(difftime(completion_date,
                                                         start_date,
                                                         units = "weeks")))/52) %>%
         rename(Phase = phase),
       mapping = aes(x = Phase,
                     y = years_to_complete,
                     group = Phase,
                     fill = Phase)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "All Completed Investigational Studies in AACT that Began On or After 01-01-1990",
       y = "Years to Complete") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Paired") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30),
        legend.position = "bottom")
